etymologies: late 17th century. Apparently from post-classical Latin quinquina cinchona tree (although this is apparently first attested later: 1747 or earlier; also kinkina) or its probable etymon French quinquina cinchona bark, variant of quinaquina quinaquina

definitions: Cinchona bark. Also more fully "quinquina bark". Now chiefly historical.
Any of several French aperitif wines flavoured with quinine.
